{
    "analysis": "Previous step: we loaded the four telemetry files and confirmed they exist and their time ranges. metric.csv contains many rows (319,703) spanning 2022-03-20 13:00:00 to 14:00:00 (UTC+8). trace.csv and log.csv cover the investigation window 2022-03-20 13:30:00 to 14:00:00 (UTC+8). error_logs.csv is empty. We therefore should proceed with metric-based preprocessing and anomaly scanning (global threshold calculation followed by incident-window filtering) to narrow candidate component-KPIs that show abnormal behavior in the 13:30–14:00 window. This is not the final answer yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, perform the following via Python and return a compact aggregate table (no more than 20 rows):\n1) For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair, compute the global P95 and P5 using the full series available in metric.csv (do NOT filter by the incident window when computing these percentiles). 2) Then filter metric.csv to the incident window March 20, 2022 13:30:00 to 14:00:00 (UTC+8) and for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: number of points in the window (window_points), count of values >= global_P95 (anomaly_count_ge_p95), earliest timestamp in the window where value >= global_P95 (earliest_anom_ts_ge_p95), count of values <= global_P5 (anomaly_count_le_p5), earliest timestamp in the window where value <= global_P5 (earliest_anom_ts_le_p5), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window. 3) Return the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) rows ranked by anomaly_count_ge_p95 + anomaly_count_le_p5 (descending). For each returned row include: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_P95, global_P5, window_points, anomaly_count_ge_p95, earliest_anom_ts_ge_p95, anomaly_count_le_p5, earliest_anom_ts_le_p5, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window. If there are ties, order by the earliest anomaly timestamp. Keep the output compact (at most 20 rows). Also report the total number of distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs scanned."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step: metric analysis scanned 5,253 distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs and ranked the top 20 by anomaly counts. All top candidates are from adservice, with every point in the 13:30–14:00 window equal to their global P95/P5 (window length 31 points; anomaly_count_ge_p95 = 31 and anomaly_count_le_p5 = 31; earliest anomaly at 2022-03-20 13:30:00 UTC+8). error_logs.csv contains no rows. Interpretation: metrics strongly highlight adservice as anomalous across many KPIs starting exactly at the window start, but metric values being identical to global percentiles for the whole window suggests stable but anomalous values (could be traffic drop, constant maxed values, or telemetry artifact). We cannot conclude root cause yet because: 1) multiple KPIs on the same service are flagged (need to determine whether adservice is the true root or downstream victim), and 2) trace analysis is required to find the most downstream faulty component in call chains and to separate service-level vs container-level faults. Next step: run trace-level anomaly aggregation to see which trace streams (service-to-service or container traces) show latency/availability degradation in the same timeframe and identify downstream faulty node/pod.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv, do the following and return a compact table (<=20 rows): 1) For each unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute global P95 and P5 across the full available series in trace.csv (do NOT filter by the incident window). 2) Then filter trace.csv to the incident window March 20, 2022 13:30:00 to 14:00:00 (UTC+8) and for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute: window_points, count of values >= global_P95 (anomaly_count_ge_p95), earliest timestamp with value >= global_P95 (earliest_anom_ts_ge_p95), count of values <= global_P5 (anomaly_count_le_p5), earliest timestamp with value <= global_P5 (earliest_anom_ts_le_p5), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window. 3) Return the top 20 (cmdb_id, trace_name) rows ranked by anomaly_count_ge_p95 + anomaly_count_le_p5 (descending). Include the total number of distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs scanned. Limit output to the requested aggregate columns and at most 20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous actions: we scanned all metrics, traces, and logs. Metric-level scanning flagged many (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs (5,253 pairs) with faults concentrated at 13:30:00 UTC+8; most fault runs span the full window (31 minutes) and have zero computed severity because their window values equal the global percentiles (P5==P95 or constant-series). Trace-level scanning showed many trace metrics constant at 0.0 (P95=P5=0.0), causing every window point to be marked but offering little discriminatory power. error_logs.csv is empty. Fault extraction produced 9,429 fault runs in total; top components by fault count included adservice and several frontend and checkoutservice pods. At this stage we cannot confidently pick two distinct root-cause events because many flagged runs are artifacts of constant-valued series. We therefore need to focus on the subset of faults that have non-zero severity (real deviation from global thresholds) and use those higher-severity faults to localize actual failures. The next step is to surface the highest-severity faults so we can inspect their components, start times, and affected KPIs and then use traces/logs to decide root cause components.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Recompute fault runs for metric.csv (use full-series percentiles as before) but focus on real deviations: 1) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute global_P95 and global_P5 using the entire series. 2) Filter to the incident window 2022-03-20 13:30:00 to 14:00:00 UTC+8 and detect consecutive-minute fault runs where value >= global_P95 OR value <= global_P5. 3) For each fault run compute severity_score as previously defined. 4) Return a compact table of the top 20 fault runs ranked by severity_score (descending). Include columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, fault_type, start_timestamp, end_timestamp, length_minutes, max_value_in_run, min_value_in_run, global_P95, global_P5, severity_score. Also return an aggregate list of components (top 10 cmdb_ids) ranked by total severity_score sum (cmdb_id, total_severity, earliest_fault_start). Keep output bounded to these aggregates (<=20 rows for faults, <=10 rows for component aggregate)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed global-threshold calculation, window filtering, and fault extraction. Summary of findings so far: many metrics and traces are constant-valued, producing many zero-severity or artifact faults. After focusing on severity, two dominant leads emerged: a high-severity node-level I/O fault on node-5 (system.io.rkb_s severity 64, full 13:30–14:00 run) and high-severity container memory-failure metrics associated with shippingservice-0 (container.node-6.container_memory_failures severity ~33, full 13:30–14:00 run). Additional notable signals include node-6 I/O elevation and short high spikes on node-1 (I/O writes and iowait). error_logs.csv is empty. We cannot yet definitively map these faults to the two distinct customer-facing failures without confirming whether the shippingservice memory-failure is a container/pod-level root cause (and whether it is downstream of impacted services) and whether node-5 I/O is an independent failure affecting different services. To proceed we must inspect metric fault details for node-5 and shippingservice-0, check traces involving shippingservice-0 (to see downstream propagation / call chain position), and check logs for any entries for these components during 13:30–14:00. This will help determine two distinct failures (component, occurrence time, and reason).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For the two top candidates (node-5 and shippingservice-0) return compact, bounded results (<=20 rows each):\n1) From the previously computed fault runs (use the kernel-stored faults table), list all fault rows for cmdb_id == 'node-5' OR cmdb_id == 'shippingservice-0' that have severity_score > 0. For each row return: cmdb_id, kpi_name, fault_type, start_timestamp, end_timestamp, length_minutes, max_value_in_run, min_value_in_run, global_P95, global_P5, severity_score. Limit to top 20 rows ordered by severity_score desc.\n2) From trace.csv, filter to the incident window (2022-03-20 13:30:00 to 14:00:00 UTC+8) and return up to 20 rows where cmdb_id is 'shippingservice-0' OR cmdb_id contains 'shippingservice' OR where trace_name mentions 'shippingservice' (to capture inbound/outbound traces). For each trace row return: timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value. Also compute for each returned (cmdb_id, trace_name) the global_P95 and global_P5 (computed over full trace series) and include them.\n3) From log.csv, filter to the incident window and return up to 20 rows where cmdb_id is 'shippingservice-0' OR cmdb_id == 'node-5' OR cmdb_id == 'node-6'. Return columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, log_name, value. Also confirm whether error_logs.csv remains empty by returning its row count.\nReturn these three compact tables only (do not print full raw time series)."
}

